                    <note xml:lang="en" type="abstract" corresp="http://syriaca.org/persons http://syriaca.org/authors">
                        <quote source="#bib721-1">Ṣawma was a monk of the Ch. of E. who, sometime
                            around 1275, set out from Dadu (also known as Khān Bālīq, i.e. modern
                            Beijing) in his native China with a younger disciple, Markos, on a
                            pilgrimage to <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/104">Jerusalem</placeName>.</quote>
                    </note>
                    <note xml:lang="en" type="abstract" resp="http://syriaca.org" corresp="http://syriaca.org/q http://syriaca.org/saints">In hagiography: <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/721">Sauma, Rabban</persName> is
                        commemorated as the monastic teacher and travelling companion of the monk
                        Markos who became the <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/810">catholicos Yahbalaha III</persName>. Acting on behalf of the
                        catholicos, Rabban Sauma travelled to <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/641">Constantinople</placeName>,
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/641">Rome</placeName> and even
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/863">Paris</placeName>.</note>
                    <floruit>
                        <date notBefore="1200" notAfter="1300" srophe:computed-end="1300-01-01" srophe:computed-start="1200-01-01" source="#bib721-1">13th cent.</date>
                    </floruit>
